          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f\left( x \right) = - 4x^2 - 3x + 7</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>F\left( x \right) = - x^4 + x^3 + 9</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec11-7">
        <p>
          Following is a statement of a theorem which can be proven using the quadratic formula.
          For this theorem, <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>,
          and <m>c</m> are real numbers.
          <ul>
            \item <em>Theorem</em> If <m>f</m> is a quadratic function of the form <m>f\left( x \right) = ax^2 + bx + c</m> and <m>ac \lt 0</m>, then the function <m>f</m> has two <m>x</m>-intercepts.
          </ul>
        </p>
        Using <em>only</em> this theorem, what can be concluded about the functions given by the following formulas?
        <ol>
