          <em>Theorem A</em>.
          If <m>f</m> is a cubic function of the form <m>f(x) = x^3 - x + b</m> and <m>b > 1</m>,
          then the function <m>f</m> has exactly one <m>x</m>-intercept.
          Following is another theorem about <m>x</m>-intercepts of functions:
          <em>Theorem B</em>.
          If <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are functions with <m>g(x) = k \cdot f(x)</m>,
          where <m>k</m> is a nonzero real number,
          then <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> have exactly the same <m>x</m>-intercepts.
          Using only these two theorems and some simple algebraic manipulations,
          what can be concluded about the functions given by the following formulas?
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(x) = x^3 - x + 7</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
